05558nam a22008535i 9780231541015DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015032306  a(OCoLC)979742555  a97802315410157 a10.7312/bilg170802doi  a(DE-B1597)468912  a(OCoLC)936070304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL2747.8b.B49 2016 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a200.9/0422300aBeyond the Secular West /ced. by Akeel Bilgrami. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Culture, and Public Life ;v2300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- t1. CAN SECULARISM TRAVEL? -- t2. THE SUFI AND THE STATE -- t3. THE INDIVIDUAL AND COLLECTIVE SELF-LIBERATION MODEL OF USTADH MAHMOUD MOHAMED TAHA -- t4. CREATING DEMOCRATICALLY FRIENDLY TWIN TOLERATIONS OUTSIDE OF LATIN CHRISTENDOM: TUNISIA -- t5. SECULARISM AND THE MEXICAN REVOLUTION -- t6. IS CONFUCIANISM SECULAR? -- t7. DISENCHANTMENT DEFERRED -- t8. AN ANCIENT INDIAN SECULAR AGE? -- t9. GANDHI’S RADICALISM: AN INTERPRETATION -- t10. A SECULAR AGE OUTSIDE LATIN CHRISTENDOM: CHARLES TAYLOR RESPONDS -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the character of secularism in countries that were not pervaded by Christianity, such as China, India, and the nations of the Middle East? To what extent is the secular an imposition of colonial rule? How does secularism comport with local religious cultures in Africa, and how does it work with local forms of power and governance in Latin America? Has modern secularism evolved organically, or is it even necessary, and has it always meant progress? A vital extension of Charles Taylor's A Secular Age, in which he exhaustively chronicled the emergence of secularism in Latin Christendom, this anthology applies Taylor's findings to secularism's global migration. Abdullahi Ahmed An-Na'im, Rajeev Bhargava, Akeel Bilgrami, Souleymane Bachir Diagne, Sudipta Kaviraj, Claudio Lomnitz, Alfred Stepan, Charles Taylor, and Peter van der Veer each explore the transformation of Western secularism beyond Europe, and the collection closes with Taylor's response to each essay. What began as a modern reaction to—as well as a stubborn extension of—Latin Christendom has become a complex export shaped by the world's religious and political systems. Brilliantly alternating between intellectual and methodological approaches, this volume fosters a greater engagement with the phenomenon across disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReligion and culture. 0aSecularism. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aAn-Na′im, Abdullahi Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhargava, Rajeev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilgrami, Akeel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilgrami, Akeel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDiagne, Souleymane Bachir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaviraj, Sudipta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLomnitz, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStepan, Alfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeer, Peter van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt